english:
  title: A Preface Given to Sunim Chol, Head of the Meditation Hall
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have traveled through many temples as the younger brother of the venerable Migong, and have formed friendships with numerous aged and accomplished monks, yet I had never once encountered the one called Chol, Head of the Meditation Hall. In the spring of the year Imjin, I was afflicted with illness and had withdrawn from receiving guests, when a certain Sunim Sho arrived bearing two texts—the Cheongnyang Practice and the Jugata—requesting that I add a final word to continue them, and moreover, acting on Sunim Chol's behalf, asked me to compose this writing. Thus pondering the remarkable character for Chol, I thought that should I ever meet him, I would surely not forget him. In the autumn of the previous year, I traveled to Heugwon and my path led through Yangju. Entering Hwegyeam Temple, I reclined in the Cheonpung Pavilion. Taking me for an elderly scholar, the monks of the temple all sought me out in rivalry. There was one called Chol who had entered into meditation practice, and so I could not discern his person. I asked Sunim Sho: "Is it the man of about thirty years, with lustrous complexion, broad brow, tall frame, and fair skin?" He replied, "No." I asked, "Is it the short, sturdy one whose speech comes rapidly, whose voice rings out like metal and stone?" He replied, "No." I asked, "Is it the one with bushy brows and white hair, broad at the shoulders and narrow below, who shuffles sideways and wheezes with each utterance?" He replied, "It seems so, yet no." I asked, "Is it the one with dark complexion and squared jaw, deep-set eyes and large mouth, who laughs mockingly at others and speaks without restraint?" He replied that it seemed truly like Chol, though he could not be certain. Sunim Sho then said, "If you were to point out each person in turn as you sit here, you would arrive at the answer. Yet the more you speak of Chol's appearance, the further you stray from truth."

    I then said, "As human hearts differ, so do their faces. Though you were to gather all people under heaven and set them before us, you could not find one that truly matches another. Thus it is fitting that in describing Chol's appearance, we find such discord." Reflecting further: if we speak of what is common to all—that eyebrows run horizontally, noses stand straight, heads are round, feet are square—then all people are the same. Yet if we speak of what differs—in height and stature, in comeliness and plainness, in thickness and fineness, in roughness and smoothness—then each person is unique, and none are alike. Those who, from what is common, establish what is different are ordinary beings, are sentient creatures. Those who, from what is different, do not establish difference are the Buddhas, are sages. This is what Hui-neng meant when he said: "Ever responding through the senses, yet raising no mark of response; discerning all dharmas, yet raising no mark of discrimination." Alas! Though all dharmas are manifold, when unified they return to one source. Though one source is unified, when dispersed it divides into manifold dharmas. Thus difference is not truly different, and sameness is not truly the same. In the practice of monks today, each believes they have attained what others have not, and when they discourse together, it amounts to no more than this. In my speaking of Chol and pointing to various persons, I failed to discern the true appearance of Chol—not only did I fail to grasp what is common, but I was truly bewildered by sameness and difference. Should one truly perceive Chol and speak truthfully of the true mind and true nature dwelling within, then it should be surrendered to a burst of laughter, and all that I have spoken would become merely a net to catch the fish—no more and no less.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hui-neng (盧能): The Sixth Patriarch of Chan Buddhism, known for his doctrine of sudden enlightenment and non-duality.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The net metaphor (筌蹄) derives from Zhuangzi: a net is a means to catch fish, words are a means to catch meaning—once the fish or meaning is caught, the tool itself is forgotten.'
  - key: ''
    value: The epistle plays with the paradox of describing the indescribable—attempting to identify a particular monk through physical characteristics while subtly arguing for the futility of such distinctions from a Buddhist philosophical perspective.
